{{Combined-marine-propulsion}}
[[Image:COSAG-diagram.png|thumb|left|Principle of a COSAG propulsion system]]
'''Combined steam and gas (COSAG)''' is a [[Marine propulsion|propulsion]] system for [[ship]]s using a combination of [[steam turbine]]s and [[gas turbine]]s to power the [[propeller shaft|shafts]]. A [[transmission (mechanics)|gearbox]] and [[clutch]]es enable either of the engines or both of them together to drive the shaft. It has the advantage of the cruising efficiency and reliability of steam and the rapid acceleration and start-up time of gas. This system was mainly used on first-generation gas-turbine ships such as the [[Royal Navy|Royal Navy's]] [[County class destroyer|''County'' class destroyer]] and [[Tribal class frigate|''Tribal'' class frigate]].

The [[Spanish aircraft carrier Dédalo]] also used it.

{{clear|left}}

